===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm|en}} ''creime, creme'', from {{etyl|xno|en}} ''creme, cresme'' (compare {{etyl|fr|-}} {{term|crème|lang=fr}}), blend of {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|chrisma|lang=en}} 'ointment' (from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|χρῖσμα|tr=chrisma|lang=grc}} 'unguent'), and {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term/t|la|crāmum}} 'skim', from {{etyl|cel-gau|en}} *''crama'' (compare {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|cramen|lang=cy}} 'scab, skin', {{etyl|br|-}} ''crammen''), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*(s)krama-}} (compare {{etyl|mga|-}} ''screm'' 'surface, skin', Dutch ''schram'' 'abrasion', {{etyl|lt|-}} ''kramas'' 'scurf'). Replaced {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|ream|lang=en}}.
Figurative sense of "most excellent element or part" appears from 1581. Verb meaning "to beat, thrash, wreck" is 1929, U.S. colloquial. The U.S. standard of identity is from [http://edocket.access.gpo.gov/cfr_2002/aprqtr/21cfr131.3.htm 21&nbsp;CFR 131.3(a)].

